# 🔍 Talentiaa Database — Data Inconsistency & Integrity Analysis

> Analysis of [talentiaa_schema.sql](file:///Users/istiakahmed/Talentiaa/talentiaa_schema.sql) (495 lines, 16 tables) and [supabase_auth_bootstrap.sql](file:///Users/istiakahmed/Talentiaa/supabase_auth_bootstrap.sql) (302 lines)

---

## Summary Table

| Severity | Count | Description |
|----------|-------|-------------|
| 🔴 CRITICAL | 3 | Will cause failures or security breaches in production |
| 🟠 HIGH | 5 | Will cause data inconsistency over time |
| 🟡 MEDIUM | 6 | Design weaknesses that can lead to dirty data |
| 🔵 LOW | 4 | Minor improvements for robustness |

---

## 🔴 CRITICAL Issues

### C1. RLS (Row Level Security) Missing on 15 out of 16 Tables

**File:** [talentiaa_schema.sql](file:///Users/istiakahmed/Talentiaa/talentiaa_schema.sql)

Only `public.users` has RLS enabled (in bootstrap file). **All other tables — `jobs`, `applications`, `resumes`, `candidate_profiles`, `notifications`, etc. — have NO RLS.**

Since Supabase clients connect **directly to the database** using the `anon` key, this means:
- ✅ Any authenticated user can **read ALL jobs, ALL applications, ALL resumes** of ALL candidates
- ✅ A candidate can **see other candidates' scores and notes**
- ✅ A candidate can **modify any job posting**
- ✅ Anyone can **delete any data** in these tables

> [!CAUTION]
> This is a **production-breaking security vulnerability**. Every table needs RLS policies before going live. Without them, your database is essentially open to any logged-in user.

**Fix:** Enable RLS and create policies for every table:
```sql
-- Example for jobs table
ALTER TABLE public.jobs ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- Recruiters see their own jobs; candidates see published jobs
CREATE POLICY jobs_select ON public.jobs FOR SELECT TO authenticated
  USING (
    recruiter_id = auth.uid()
    OR public.current_user_role() = 'admin'
    OR (status = 'published' AND application_deadline >= current_date)
  );

-- Only the owning recruiter or admin can update
CREATE POLICY jobs_update ON public.jobs FOR UPDATE TO authenticated
  USING (recruiter_id = auth.uid() OR public.current_user_role() = 'admin');

-- Only recruiter/admin can insert
CREATE POLICY jobs_insert ON public.jobs FOR INSERT TO authenticated
  WITH CHECK (recruiter_id = auth.uid() OR public.current_user_role() = 'admin');
```

---

### C2. `password_hash` Column is Dead — Constraint Creates False Safety

**File:** [talentiaa_schema.sql:152](file:///Users/istiakahmed/Talentiaa/talentiaa_schema.sql#L152)

```sql
constraint users_password_or_oauth_chk
  check (password_hash is not null or oauth_provider is not null)
```

With Supabase Auth, passwords are managed in `auth.users`, NOT in `public.users`. The bootstrap trigger [handle_auth_user_created](file:///Users/istiakahmed/Talentiaa/supabase_auth_bootstrap.sql#L65-L114) **never sets `password_hash`** — it always sets `oauth_provider` to `'supabase'` or `'google'`, which satisfies the constraint.

**Problem:** `password_hash` will **always be NULL** in production. The column is useless dead weight and the constraint gives a false sense of security — it looks like it's enforcing "must have a password or OAuth", but it's actually just enforcing "must have oauth_provider set".

**Fix:**
```sql
-- Remove the dead column and useless constraint
ALTER TABLE public.users DROP COLUMN password_hash;
ALTER TABLE public.users DROP CONSTRAINT users_password_or_oauth_chk;
```

---

### C3. `auth_sessions` Table is Completely Redundant

**File:** [talentiaa_schema.sql:168-181](file:///Users/istiakahmed/Talentiaa/talentiaa_schema.sql#L168-L181)

Supabase manages sessions internally via `auth.sessions`. Your `public.auth_sessions` table with `refresh_token_hash`, `device_label`, etc. **will never be populated** by Supabase's auth system. No trigger or function writes to it.

**Result:** An empty orphan table sitting in production, confusing developers.

**Fix:** Drop the table entirely, or if you need custom session tracking, build an explicit integration.

```sql
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS public.auth_sessions;
```

